# Cursor Rules for Python Development - Audio Analyser Project

## Project Overview
This is a Python project for audio analysis. Follow these rules to maintain code quality, consistency, and best practices.

## Code Style and Standards

### Python Style Guidelines
- Follow PEP 8 style guidelines strictly
- Use Black formatter with 88-character line length
- Use isort for import organization with Black profile
- Maximum line length: 88 characters (Black default)
- Use 4 spaces for indentation, never tabs
- Use snake_case for variables, functions, and modules
- Use PascalCase for classes
- Use UPPER_CASE for constants

### Type Annotations
- Always use type hints for function parameters and return values
- Use `typing` module for complex types (List, Dict, Optional, Union, etc.)
- Use `from __future__ import annotations` for forward references
- Prefer `list[str]` over `List[str]` (Python 3.9+ style)

### Documentation
- Write docstrings for all public functions, classes, and modules
- Use Google-style docstrings format
- Include type information in docstrings when helpful
- Add examples for complex functions
- Document all parameters, return values, and exceptions

### Error Handling
- Use specific exception types, not bare `except:`
- Always handle exceptions appropriately
- Use `logging` module for error reporting
- Create custom exceptions when needed
- Use context managers (`with` statements) for resource management

## Project Structure

### Directory Organization
- `src/` - Main source code
- `tests/` - Test files (mirror src structure)
- `docs/` - Documentation
- `scripts/` - Utility scripts
- `venv/` - Virtual environment (excluded from git)

### File Naming
- Use snake_case for Python files
- Test files should start with `test_`
- Configuration files use appropriate extensions (.toml, .yaml, .json)

### Import Organization
- Standard library imports first
- Third-party imports second
- Local application imports last
- Use absolute imports when possible
- Group imports with blank lines between groups

## Testing Guidelines

### Test Structure
- Use pytest as the testing framework
- Place tests in `tests/` directory
- Mirror the source code structure in tests
- Use descriptive test function names starting with `test_`
- Use fixtures for common setup/teardown

### Test Coverage
- Aim for high test coverage (>90%)
- Test both happy paths and edge cases
- Use parametrized tests for multiple scenarios
- Mock external dependencies
- Test error conditions and exceptions

### Test Organization
- One test file per source module
- Group related tests in classes
- Use descriptive test names that explain the scenario
- Keep tests simple and focused

## Development Workflow

### Virtual Environment
- Always use virtual environment for development
- Activate venv before running any Python commands
- Install dependencies from requirements files
- Use `pip install -e .` for development installation

### Git Practices
- Use descriptive commit messages
- Follow conventional commit format when possible
- Create feature branches for new features
- Keep commits atomic and focused
- Use `.gitignore` to exclude unnecessary files

### Code Quality Tools
- Run Black formatter before committing
- Use flake8 for linting
- Use mypy for type checking
- Use pytest for testing
- Use pre-commit hooks for automation

## Music Analysis Specific Guidelines

### Audio Processing
- Use librosa for audio analysis when needed
- Handle different audio formats appropriately
- Consider memory usage for large audio files
- Use appropriate sample rates and bit depths

### Data Handling
- Use pandas for structured data analysis
- Use numpy for numerical computations
- Consider performance for large datasets
- Use appropriate data types to save memory

### Visualization
- Use matplotlib or seaborn for plotting
- Create publication-ready figures
- Use consistent color schemes
- Include proper labels and legends

## Performance Considerations

### Optimization
- Profile code before optimizing
- Use vectorized operations (numpy) over loops
- Consider memory usage for large datasets
- Use appropriate data structures
- Cache expensive computations when possible

### Resource Management
- Close files and connections properly
- Use context managers for resource cleanup
- Consider memory usage for audio processing
- Handle large files efficiently

## Security and Best Practices

### Security
- Never commit sensitive information (API keys, passwords)
- Use environment variables for configuration
- Validate user inputs
- Sanitize file paths and names

### Code Quality
- Write self-documenting code
- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Keep functions small and focused
- Avoid deep nesting
- Use list/dict comprehensions when appropriate

## Dependencies and Package Management

### Requirements Management
- Pin major versions in requirements.txt
- Use requirements-dev.txt for development dependencies
- Keep dependencies up to date
- Document any special installation requirements

### Package Structure
- Use `__init__.py` files appropriately
- Organize code into logical modules
- Use relative imports within packages
- Follow Python packaging best practices

## Debugging and Logging

### Logging
- Use the `logging` module instead of print statements
- Set appropriate log levels
- Include context in log messages
- Use structured logging when possible

### Debugging
- Use debugger (pdb) for complex issues
- Add temporary logging for debugging
- Use assertions for development checks
- Remove debug code before committing

## Code Review Guidelines

### Review Checklist
- Code follows style guidelines
- Type hints are present and correct
- Tests are comprehensive and pass
- Documentation is complete
- Error handling is appropriate
- Performance considerations are addressed

### Review Process
- Review for correctness and clarity
- Check for security issues
- Verify test coverage
- Ensure documentation is updated
- Consider maintainability

## Continuous Integration

### Automated Checks
- Run tests on all commits
- Check code style and formatting
- Run type checking
- Verify test coverage
- Build documentation

### Deployment
- Use version tags for releases
- Document deployment process
- Test in staging environment
- Monitor application after deployment

## Additional Notes

- Always consider the user experience
- Write code that others can understand and maintain
- Follow the principle of least surprise
- Prefer explicit over implicit
- Keep it simple and readable
- Document complex algorithms and business logic
- Consider edge cases and error conditions
- Use appropriate data structures for the task
- Optimize for readability first, performance second
